I often wondered about the legacy of persecution that some Christians talk about. You have to wonder why that there are any left with all of the ones that were fed to the lions. Except we know that wasn't true because the coliseums were reserved for gladiator fights. If any animals were used, they were in the back woods and they weren't lions but probably dogs or wolves. Now a Notre Dame professor has shed new light on the whole martyrdom question. Candida Moss, a Professor of New Testament Studies, has written "The Myth of Persecution: How Early Christians Invented a Story of Martyrdom " I heard an in depth interview of her on the Reasonable Doubt podcast.She started off the interview by addressing the most frequent instance cited as proof of Christian persecution. That would be the law mandated by Decius in 250 CE that all people that did not convert to the Roman religion be executed. Professor Moss states that the evidence shows that this particular persecution may have lasted as little as one month. It was really an attempt by Decius to legitimize his regime and to bring the country together. Such edicts were not uncommon She goes on to talk about ideas that were common to various groups, Christians , Jews, Romans and Greeks. And it was the idea of a noble death. The idea that a living a good life and dying for principle was something that all agreed was a noble pursuit. For that reason, Professor Moss believes that many of the martyrdom stories were simply made up to follow a particular story archetype. The heroes or heroines do or say things that were said in a Greek or Roman story about dying a noble death. She then relates another occurrence where just after Constantine installed Christianity as the state religion, scribes were under pressure to churn out as many stories of martyred Christians as they could. Here rather than craft a story that was like some sort of epic , the same stories were used and Christian names were installed as the protagonists. She termed this the cookie cutter martyrdom method.Moss also talks about the Nero persecutions. She mirrors what I have read from other sources. But she adds some things. For one thing she says that Tacitus writing some 50 years after the event occurs. outlines the frequently cited persecution. However, if Nero persecuted anyone , it wasn't Christians. For one thing in 64 CE, Christians were not referred to as Christians. Paul never used a term and it didn't start being used until the turn of the first century. Christianity was such a new sect that it is doubtful that they would have even come to Nero's attention. Rather this was probably a hatchet job by Tacitus, who didn't like Nero.She said that dying for Christ had great appeal among the early Christians. She relates a story where Christians wanted to die like Christ. This was before suicide became taboo. They went to the local governor and asked to be executed like Christ. He said that he wanted no part of their death and state that he was sure that they could secure enough rope to do the job themselves. But that early Christians would die so easily for their faith is eerily similar to the same behaviors that take place even today.Professor Moss thinks that Christians should not try to use a legacy of persecution that never really existed. And rather than calling the school prayer ban, persecution, she says the worry should be what is being taught in schools. Maybe we can all agree on that.
