Updated Aug. 23, 2010 7:32 p.m. ET
The U.S. Justice Department said it is stepping up efforts to combat financial fraud in the Gulf of Mexico, amid fears that the billions of dollars offered to compensate oil spill victims could be a magnet for criminals. Justice officials will announce on Tuesday that the National Center for Disaster Fraud, set up five years ago to act as a clearinghouse for cases stemming from Hurricane Katrina, will turn its focus to cases related to the oil spill. The department will investigate "any way that people are trying to take advantage of this disaster to benefit themselves fraudulently at the expense of others," Lanny Breuer, the Assistant Attorney General in charge of the Justice Department's criminal division, said in an interview. The NCDF, based in Baton Rouge, La., has set up a telephone hotline for people to report potential fraud, anonymously if necessary. Starting this week, the number will be widely publicized in billboards and posters throughout the region, officials said. Officials and BP
