PLC have become concerned that the $20 billion fund set up by BP to compensate those damaged by the oil spill could draw large numbers of bogus claims. According to one person familiar with the matter, a fund of that size will attract fraudsters "like bees to a honey pot." "Wherever there is money made available for legitimate assistance … there will be an irreducible minimum of individuals who will try to take advantage of that," said Jim Letten, U.S. Attorney for the Eastern District of Louisiana, who oversees the disaster fraud center. But BP and law enforcement officials are also concerned about a much broader array of potential fraud. The energy company has recently issued warnings on social networks like Facebook about fake "claims adjusters" who, it says, are contacting people offering to file claims for a fee. "We're saying to people: Beware, there are people around. They're trying to get money from you," a BP spokesman said. BP executives have said little about the possibility of fraud in public since outgoing chief executive Tony Hayward was criticized for suggesting that some people would try to take advantage of the compensation effort. "This is America," Mr. Hayward said earlier this year. "Come on. We're going to have lots of illegitimate claims. We all know that." The Justice Department's efforts come after control of the fund was officially transferred on Monday to the official appointed by the White House to administer it, Kenneth Feinberg. Mr. Feinberg and other officials have previously expressed their concern that the fund could be flooded with bogus claims. Mr. Breuer said that any suspected fraudulent claims uncovered by Mr. Feinberg would be referred directly to the Justice Department's criminal division for investigation. They will target only those claimants who knowingly lie in their applications, not anyone who has made an unwitting mistake, officials said. The Justice Department center that will investigate the cases has received and screened more than 39,000 complaints of disaster fraud following floods, tornadoes, earthquakes and wildfires. More than 25,000 of those complaints were referred to law enforcement for investigation, according to the Justice Department. The department has so far charged more 1,300 defendants in fraud cases related to Hurricanes Katrina, Rita and Wilma. Write to Thomas Catan at thomas.catan@wsj.com Email
