By
Nadya Masidlover
December 2, 2011
A tale of unlikely friendship has become this year's unexpected home-grown box-office hit in France, leaving Steven Spielberg's "The Adventures of Tintin" and other Hollywood productions behind. A scene from France's 'Intouchables.' Gaumont "Intouchables" ("Untouchables"), a $12 million film in which a quadriplegic millionaire hires a young black home-care aide, has attracted more than 10 million viewers since it opened in French theaters four weeks ago. (To be sure, "Tintin" has proved a hit as well, with about five million French viewers since its Oct. 26 debut, according to French cinema association CBO-Box Office.) The millionaire in "Intouchables" is played by François Cluzet, a veteran who starred in the 2006 international hit thriller "Tell No One." Up-and-coming stand-up comic Omar Sy plays the aide. Co-directors Eric Toledano and Olivier Nakache were inspired by a 2004 documentary; their fictional version is set to be distributed in around 40 countries. U.S. producer Harvey Weinstein of Weinstein Co. bought the rights to a remake before the film had finished being cut, Mr. Toledano said. Weinstein Co. declined to comment. The studio has said it plans a U.S. release next year. The box-office performance of "Intouchables" demonstrates how France is still resisting the dominance of U.S. films. Out of the 575 films released in France last year, 270 were French-led productions. With more than 5.6% of global cinema ticket sales last year, France's film market is the third biggest in the world, after the U.S. and Japan, according to data from IHS Screen. Before "Intouchables" hits the U.S., French filmmakers are hoping to conquer U.S. theaters with "The Artist," a mostly silent, black-and-white comedy about an early Hollywood star that won the New York Film Critics Circle award for best picture of 2011 this week. Write to Nadya Masidlover at nadya.masidlover@dowjones.com Email
