Updated June 13, 2009 12:01 a.m. ET
New York Rare is the performing artist who turns up his nose at the reassuring sound of applause—even when it comes at an inopportune moment. But I know a fair number of anxious audience members who live in fear of clapping at the wrong time, as well as others who believe that when it comes to expressing approval of a performance, silence is golden. Go to a classical concert and you’ll see what I mean: Anyone who dares to clap in between the movements of a symphony is likely to get glared at, or even shushed. The purpose of these signs of disapproval, so far as I can tell, is to encourage the offender to slink home in red-faced shame, never to be seen again. Enlarge Image
Randy Jones Playgoers are less inclined to frown on untimely applause, though some would have it otherwise. I recently received an email from a reader in Washington, D.C., who made a special trip to New York to see the Broadway revival of Samuel Beckett’s “Waiting for Godot.” He was startled by the fact that “the audience broke out into applause whenever an actor came onstage—it felt like we were at a taping of a sitcom—as well as after anything that could be described as a ‘performance’ of some sort. A friend told me that this is common on Broadway. Is it because of the tourists, or something that’s part of the culture of Broadway itself? And do you agree that it is much better to let the actors go on uninterrupted and express your appreciation at the end? Or am I just being parochial?” I can report from first-hand experience that American playgoers aren’t the only ones who clap whenever they please. Just last week I flew to Canada to see a performance of Oscar Wilde’s “The Importance of Being Earnest” at the Stratford Shakespeare Festival, and the audience responded to the show and its performers in exactly the same way as did the Broadway audience described by my correspondent. It didn’t bother me in the least: “The Importance of Being Earnest” is, after all, one of the greatest comedies ever written, and I can’t see much difference between laughing and clapping. As for the applause that greets the actors in “Waiting for Godot,” it’s worth pointing out that three of them, Nathan Lane, Bill Irwin and John Goodman, are stars (albeit of very different sorts). It’s long been common, on Broadway and elsewhere, to mark the first entrance of a star with a burst of applause. But is it right for so deeply serious a play as “Waiting for Godot” to be interrupted by such public displays of affection? Yes, “Godot” is a modern classic, and a thoroughly unsettling one—but it’s also a funny play, one in which comedy is used to heighten the audience’s awareness of its own existential dilemma. A performance of “Godot” at which no one laughed or clapped would be a performance that no one had understood. Classical music is, or can be, a different matter—but who says that it’s wrong to clap between movements? Alex Ross, the music critic of The New Yorker, has looked into the matter and reports that “until the beginning of the 20th century, applause between movements and even during movements was the sign of a knowledgeable, appreciative audience, not of an ignorant one.” Pierre Monteux, the great French conductor who gave the premiere of “The Rite of Spring,” was born in 1875, which made him old enough to remember how things were in the 19th century. “I do have one big complaint about audiences in all countries, and that is their artificial restraint from applause between movements of a concerto or symphony,” he said in 1959. “Of course applause should be spontaneous, not dutiful, but often it is the most natural thing to applaud between movements.” I couldn’t agree more. If you don’t feel moved to clap at the end of a first-rate performance of, say, the spectacular quick-step march that is the third movement of Tchaikovsky’s “Pathétique” Symphony, you probably need to loosen up. I’ve long thought that opera buffs and balletomanes have a saner attitude toward applause: They clap whenever they like something, and cheer when they like it a lot. Unlike their po-faced concert-hall brethren, they understand that theater is a social art, and that any public performance, be it of “Swan Lake,” Beethoven’s Ninth or “Shrek the Musical,” is by definition a social occasion as well as an artistic one. Human beings come to performances in order to enjoy art, and to have their pleasure enhanced by the presence of their fellow creatures. In a perfect world, every play would be a festival and every concert a celebration. Are there occasions when silence is both socially and artistically appropriate? Sure. At the end of a symphony or a play that ends quietly, the most eloquent tribute that you can possibly pay to the performers on stage is to leave your hands in your lap, take a deep breath and let it out very, very slowly. Then, and only then, does the moment come to break the collective stillness and express your appreciation by clapping. The rule is simple: When in doubt, wait—then let ’er rip. You’ll be glad you did. —Mr. Teachout, the Journal’s drama critic, writes “Sightings” every other Saturday and blogs about the arts at www.terryteachout.com. Write to him at tteachout@wsj.com.
